<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-061-154 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 238 617</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 10 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New for PC: school geography program ported to DOS. (CrosscountryCanada)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Didatech Software Ltd. (Product enhancement).andO;Product:   Crosscountry Canada (Educational software) (Product enhancement).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersEnhancementsGeographyMS-DOSSoftware Migration.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NEW FOR PC: School Geography Program Ported to DOS 09/10/91 BURNABY, BRITISHCOLUMBIA, CANADA, 1991 SEP 10 (NB) -- Didatech Software has announced aversion of Crosscountry Canada, its educational geography program, to run onIBM and compatible personal computers.andP;  The software was previously availablefor the Apple II line.andM;Crosscountry Canada lets children pretend to be truck drivers deliveringgoods to 80 cities and towns across Canada.andP;  According to the company, theprogram helps students learn to read maps as well as develop record-keepingand math skills as they try to control their mileage and expenses.andM;Brian Sellstedt, director of sales and marketing, told Newsbytes his companyhopes the DOS version will help it increase sales to the home market, whereDOS machines are prevalent.andM;He added, though, that there is a good deal of demand for the new version inschools.andP;  &quot;We have people who have had standing orders with us....literallyfor months,&quot; to ship the DOS product as soon as it became available, he said.andM;Didatech also sells Crosscountry USA, Crosscountry California, andCrosscountry Texas.andP;  Crosscountry USA has been available for DOS computersfor about six months, Sellstedt said.andM;The company is talking with one U.S.andP;  state and several Canadian provincesabout more localized versions of the product, Sellstedt said.andP;  He added thatthere have been requests for versions of the existing packages to run on theApple Macintosh, but &quot;I can't say that is going to be imminent right now.&quot;andM;A home edition of Crosscountry Canada costs US$49, while the school editionis US$57 to US$67.andP;  Lab packs, site licenses, and district licenses are alsoavailable.andM;(Grant Buckler/19910910/Press Contact: Brian Sellstedt, Didatech Software,604-299-4435 or 800-665-0667 (U.S.andP;  only), fax 604-299-2428)</TEXT></DOC>